Project 1 - Happy and Unhappy Customers¶

Introduction¶

Background:¶

We are one of the fastest growing startups in the logistics and delivery domain. We work with several partners and make on-demand delivery to our customers. From operational standpoint we have been facing several different challenges and everyday we are trying to address these challenges.

We thrive on making our customers happy. As a growing startup, with a global expansion strategy we know that we need to make our customers happy and the only way to do that is to measure how happy each customer is. If we can predict what makes our customers happy or unhappy, we can then take necessary actions.

Getting feedback from customers is not easy either, but we do our best to get constant feedback from our customers. This is a crucial function to improve our operations across all levels.

We recently did a survey to a select customer cohort. You are presented with a subset of this data. We will be using the remaining data as a private test set.

Data Description:¶

  • Y = target attribute (Y) with values indicating 0 (unhappy) and 1 (happy) customers
  • X1 = my order was delivered on time
  • X2 = contents of my order was as I expected
  • X3 = I ordered everything I wanted to order
  • X4 = I paid a good price for my order
  • X5 = I am satisfied with my courier
  • X6 = the app makes ordering easy for me

Attributes X1 to X6 indicate the responses for each question and have values from 1 to 5 where the smaller number indicates less and the higher number indicates more towards the answer.

Goal(s):¶

Predict if a customer is happy or not based on the answers they give to questions asked. Success Metrics:

Reach 73% accuracy score or above, or convince us why your solution is superior. We are definitely interested in every solution and insight you can provide us.

Try to submit your working solution as soon as possible. The sooner the better. Bonus(es):

We are very interested in finding which questions/features are more important when predicting a customer’s happiness. Using a feature selection approach show us understand what is the minimal set of attributes/features that would preserve the most information about the problem while increasing predictability of the data we have. Is there any question that we can remove in our next survey?

%%capture

def run_single_regressions(y_df, x_df):
    results = []
    pred = []
    models = []

    for col in x_df.columns:
        X = df[col]
        X = sm.add_constant(X)

        # Fit the regression model
        model = sm.Logit(y_df, X).fit()
        models.append(model)

        # Predict
        pred.append(model.predict(X))

        # Collect the results
        results.append({
            'Variable': col,
            'Coefficient': model.params[1],
            'Intercept': model.params[0],
            'P-Value': model.pvalues[1],
            # 'R-Squared': model.rsquared
        })
    return results, pred, models


# Return results and setup for cm
results, pred, models = run_single_regressions(df['Y'], df[df.columns[1:]])

Aggregate Performance Results¶

I wanted to analyze which data splits and models perform best, so I used LazyPredict to run multiple models while logging their performance and aggregating accuracy results across 50 seeds.

Looking at the results, I saw that model accuracy and standard deviation tend to have diminishing returns at around a 0.55 split between train and test sets.

Regarding accuracy or the best models, BernoulliNB, ExtraTreesClassifier, and XGBClassifier had good accuracy scores while keeping a low standard deviation across our seeds. These should also be good models for capturing non-linear relationships between y and X.

Table Name and What I Measured:

  • mean_by_level: This is the average accuracy for models across all seeds.
  • std_by_level: This is the average standard deviation for models across all seeds.
  • mean_by_split: This is the average accuracy for splits across all models.
  • std_by_split: This is the average standard deviation for splits across all models.

These are violin plots aggregating accuracy scores for specific models accross splits from 0.2 to 0.8. Typcially for each of these plots, we can see that around the 0.5 to 0.6 split range, model accuracy tends to be fairly consistent accross seeds. Anywhere within this range seems most reasonable to tune our models, so I ended up choosing 0.55 to be the split.

Run Models¶

Just tried to keep models simple and low complexity. To prevent over fitting, the confusion matrices are checked to make sure models are using balanced strategies. The current parameters are from after using gridsearch to optimize.

I also added in voting models to see if strategies are diverse or unique enough to improve results.

Model Performance Results¶

For the accuracy scoring, I used 'recall for 0', and forced a balanced training dataset between classes 0 and 1 to make sure models didn't prioritize class 1 over 0. I made the swap to 'recall for 0' because having a focus on unhappy customers might give us some insights on where the business is struggling to maintain customer satisfaction.

I used two benchmarks, a naive strategy, and a random strategy, to create a baseline for our models to compare against. There is a greater focus to beat the random strategy rather than the naive. The naive model essentially shows an over fitting model.

In [13]:
# Functions & Results ---------------------------------------------------------
'''
- recall score
- confusion
- classification report
'''


def get_recall_score(x):
    model = fitted_models[x]

    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    result = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=0)
    return x, result


def get_confusion_matricies(x):
    try:
        model = fitted_models[x]

        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

        result = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
        return x, result
    except Exception:
        return x, None


def get_classification_report(x):
    model = fitted_models[x]

    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    result = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
    return x, result


recall_results = dict(map(get_recall_score, fitted_models))

confusion_matricies = dict(map(get_confusion_matricies, fitted_models))

classification_report_results = dict(
    map(get_classification_report, fitted_models))
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Benchmarks ------------------------------------------------------------------
'''
- naive
- mean
'''


def calculate_random_predictions(y_train, y_test):
    unique, counts = np.unique(y_train, return_counts=True)
    class_probs = counts / len(y_train)  # Probabilities for y=0 and y=1
    random_y = np.random.choice(unique, size=len(y_test), p=class_probs)
    return random_y


# based on train class distributions - keeps being random each time I run?
baseline_random = recall_score(
    y_test,
    calculate_random_predictions(y_train, y_test),
    pos_label=0
    )

baseline_mean = recall_score(
    y_test,
    [0] * len(y_test),
    pos_label=0
    )

HyperOpt¶

To further fine tune our selected model, we'll use an objective function and a new scoring method to improve our model. A new scoring method is needed since optimizing for recall for 0 would likely result in over fitting.

The new scoring method I used is the 'Matthews correlation coefficient', which returns a more balanced score. This should make sure that models are not over fitting when tuning.

Three different models using ExtraTreesClassifier were made for:

  • no feature reduction and just further tuning our prior model.
  • manually picking the best features as decided from our prior results for feature importance.
  • using recursive feature elimination to reduce to 3 of our best predictors and then tuning the model.

# =============================================================================
# Apply HyperOpt
# =============================================================================

# variables

final_scores = {}

# Create Hyperopt Class


class HyperOptClassifier:
    def __init__(
            self, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, sample_weights):

        self.space = space
        self.X_train = X_train
        self.X_test = X_test
        self.y_train = y_train
        self.y_test = y_test
        self.sample_weights = sample_weights

    def objective(self, params):
        model = ExtraTreesClassifier(**params)

        model = model.fit(
            self.X_train,
            self.y_train,
            sample_weight=self.sample_weights
            )

        y_pred = model.predict(self.X_test)

        # confusion matrix
        tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred).ravel()

        # TNR
        # score = tn / (tn + fp)  # TNR (overfits...)
        # score = tn / (tn + fn)  # NPV
        score = matthews_corrcoef(y_test, y_pred)  # mcc

        # return negative of the score
        return {'loss': -score, 'status': STATUS_OK}

    def run_optimization(self, space, evals=50):
        best = fmin(
            fn=self.objective,
            space=self.space,
            algo=tpe.suggest,
            max_evals=evals
            )

        print("Best hyperparameters:", best)

        return space_eval(self.space, best)


# Define the hyperparameter search space
space = {
    'n_estimators':  scope.int(hp.quniform('n_estimators', 10, 200, 10)),
    'max_depth': scope.int(hp.quniform('max_depth', 1, 15, 1)),
    'min_samples_split': scope.int(hp.quniform('min_samples_split', 2, 15, 1)),
    'min_samples_leaf': scope.int(hp.quniform('min_samples_leaf', 1, 15, 1)),

    'min_weight_fraction_leaf': hp.uniform(
        'min_weight_fraction_leaf', 0.0, 0.5),

    'max_leaf_nodes': scope.int(hp.quniform(
        'max_leaf_nodes', 2, 15, 1)),

    'max_features': hp.choice('max_features', ['sqrt', 'log2', None]),
    'min_impurity_decrease': hp.uniform('min_impurity_decrease', 0.0, 0.2),
    'ccp_alpha': hp.uniform('ccp_alpha', 0.0, 0.1),
    'max_samples': scope.int(hp.quniform('max_samples', 1, 55, 1)),
    'random_state': seed,  # Fixed Parameters...
    'bootstrap': True,
    'n_jobs': -1,
    'class_weight': {0: 1.025, 1: 0.975}
    }

# Hyperopt:ExtraTreesClassifier -----------------------------------------------
hpyer_opt1 = HyperOptClassifier(  # set new object
    X_train,
    X_test,
    y_train,
    y_test,
    sample_weights
    )
best = hpyer_opt1.run_optimization(space)

# create model and fit
model = ExtraTreesClassifier(
    **best,
    )
model = model.fit(X_train, y_train, sample_weight=sample_weights)

# return results
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

final_scores['Hyperopt:ExtraTreesClassifier'] = recall_score(

Conclusions¶

Regarding the Goals of the Project¶

Reach 73% accuracy score or above, or convince us why your solution is superior. We are definitely interested in every solution and insight you can provide us.¶

I can reach a fairly accurate model of 88% accuracy with recall for 0, even with a 0.55 split.

However, I recommend focusing on unhappy customers, as this would have a greater business impact by providing insights to improve customer satisfaction rather than finding what is currently working. For instance, the most important feature to indentifying unhappy customers was the survey question, 'I am satisfied with my courier'. This suggests there may be opportunities to provide better training to ensure more positive customer experiences.

We are very interested in finding which questions/features are more important when predicting a customer’s happiness.¶

When predicting a customer's happiness, specifically Y=1, predictors such as X1 would be the best, with X3, X5, and X6 showing some promise. On the otherside, predictors such as X1, X4, and X5 were fairly important features for Y=0.

Using a feature selection approach show us understand what is the minimal set of attributes/features that would preserve the most information about the problem while increasing predictability of the data we have.¶

You could reduce the feature set down to 3 predictors and still see similar results, but I wouldn't recommend removing any predictors at this stage and just use all predictors for model prediction. This is due to the relatively low number of data points and the nature of the problem being fairly non-linear. Also, reducing the number of features for our models tended to make them approach a more naive strategy, so models will probably be more general with more predictors at this stage.

Is there any question that we can remove in our next survey?¶

The questions are fairly good, but I would recommend tuning these questions to better capture both existing happy and unhappy customers better. This is because for some of the questions, respondents who would reply negatively would not be customers in the first place.

For instance, the question, 'I ordered everything I wanted to order', wouldn't capture customers that would say 'no' or give a low score because they wouldn't have made an order in the first place. Looking at the very first violin chart for X3, you can see that both happy and unhappy customers tended to give a neutral 3 score, which tells me that they are probably didn't give the question much thought since it didn't really apply to them. All customers in this dataset would have ordered what they wanted to order, otherwise they wouldn't have ordered in the first place or be a customer.

The same can be said for the question, 'I paid a good price for my order'. Customers that have paid for a delivery have already essentially said that they 'paid a good price for my order', if it wasn't a good price they wouldn't have ordered in the first place.

Overall, rephrasing some of these questions would be a good idea to capture more polarizing groups between happy and unhappy customers while making sure all respondent can possibly answer both positively and negatively to their experiences.
